metadata.name: Magic Board #100
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Glitchy Masks #13
metadata.description:
A big thank you to Aleksandra from https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Aleksandra for their assistance with the code!

In this project, I explored the concept of randomness and was pleasantly surprised by the results. After a few iterations, masks began to emerge. I added a mirroring effect to enhance the visual and added eyes for added realism. The end result is a series of intriguing masks, created through the use of randomness and artistic experimentation.

metadata.name: Gentrax EP #170
metadata.description:
Gentrax EP is a generative audiovisual artwork. Each iteration produces a generative house/garage track ~3 minutes in length while drawing out accompanying artwork. Live piece is aspect ratio agnostic and scales to any window size, but an aspect of 1:1.414 is preferred and can be set with an URL parameter.

Audio controls:
1-7: Channel mutes/unmutes
a: Filter up 
z: Filter down
c: Flanger on/off
v: Reverb (cycle thru three settings)
q: Switch bassline octave&seq (cycle thru three settings)
b: Portamento on/off

Visual controls: 
p: Fast forward to final artwork
o: Save canvas

Url parameters: 
&w=800 : Set width of canvas. If aspect ratio is not defined, artwork will be in preferred aspect ratio (1.41414)
&a=1.5 : Set aspect ratio. number <1 = Wide canvas
&wl=1 : Locks canvas aspect ratio to preferred 


made with p5.js & tone.js
Using tonejs synthesis for bass plus oneshot samples from various drum machines & Alpha Juno 2
<3

CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.description:
Œ± -> Œ≤ is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

metadata.name: Anachronous #141
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

metadata.name: Ontologies #159
metadata.description:
A system designed to make art out of its own code. 

What is the 'artful' component of generative art - is it the algorithm's form or the aesthetics of individual outputs? Ontologies brings the code out of the shadows into the foreground, nudging the viewer to consider this system's recursive existence. 

Is there something vaguely mortal, or at least vulnerable, about a system 'aware' of its own inner workings (like a person contemplating their DNA code)? Our use of computers to express incomputable human inspiration and creativity suggests that we already see them as more than just tools or calculating machines. So who is the artist, and what is the art?

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: La Invernada #4
metadata.description:
This project is about my mother's lifestyle. Her work is breeding and herding goats, cows and horses.
She lives a cyclical life marked by two major stages during her livestock year: "La Veranada" and "La Invernada". My last work was about "La Veranada", this work is about "La Invernada", I hope you enjoy it.
Time in the life of a criancero is cyclical. Everything comes and goes, and comes back and comes back. Nature, so present, so in connection with the man and woman who inhabit it, marks the times perhaps like no other place.
 The succession of the seasons, the weather, the buds and "La Invernada", the sowing, the pastures, the harvest and the snows.
"La Invernada" is the place during what we could call the long winter, that is, from April to November.
"La Invernada" is down in the plains, in the pampas, in accessible places, where it is easy to supply forage to the goats that calve between October and November.
The "Criancero" rides a horse every day and, accompanied by his dogs, goes to "watch" the goats. They distinguish them in the distance. Every day is the same and different at the same time. Caring for, watching over and keeping the goats healthy and safe.
"El puesto" is their home. In the stall they use the water from the river, which they draw with a water pump, for their hygiene. Water for consumption is brought in jerry cans from "Vertientes", located about 10 km away.
 The hens roam freely throughout the day, when night comes some go to sleep in the "gallinero" and others simply sleep on small plants.
As you can see, life here is simple, solitary and with a lot of work.
I want to thank all those who have taken the trouble to read the story. I hope you liked it.
You can find real photos and videos of "La Invernada" on my twitter profile.

Features:
10 Color Palettes.
10 types of Animal pen.
Various types of chickens.
14 types of herbs.
10 types of flowerpot.
4 types of trees.
7 types of rivers.
The barn has 4 sizes.
The moon has a very varied range of x and y positions.
6% chance of getting snowy weather in the piece.


Press "S" in live mode to save the 2600 x 3000 image.
Note that the algorithm may take some time to run.
Created by Fernando. NFT 2.0 license.

metadata.name: Cyanotypes #275
metadata.description:
This is an algorithmic tribute to the pioneering work of Anna Atkins (1799-1871). Considered by many the first female photographer, Atkins learned about the cyanotype process soon after it was invented by John Herschel, a family friend. As a botanist, she had the idea of using the new technique to produce contact prints of plants. Her investigations succeeded in capturing the nuances in morphology and the delicate details of many species.

In 1843 she published ‚ÄúBritish Algae: Cyanotype impressions‚Äù, the first published book to use a photographic process for the illustrations. Each copy gathered around 400 prints, each of them individually produced from a different specimen. Thus, all books featured the same species, but each of them was different, in a process that was itself generative in a certain way. Today, about 17 copies of the book are preserved in different institutions. Atkins went on to publish two more books in the following years, with the help of her friend Anne Dixon, dedicated to various ferns and plants.

‚ÄúCyanotypes‚Äù pays homage to her wonderful work, which sits at the intersection between science and art, and used technology in a novel way to capture the beauty of nature. Here things are taken one step forward, to generate algorithmic simulations of plants, ferns, and algae, which are the work of fantasy and not necessarily faithful to the traits of any real species.

The work features 28 basic configurations, each of them in turn capable of unlimited variations. As was the case with the prints from ‚ÄúBritish Algae‚Äù, every image is at the same time part of a series and unique. 

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 800 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be very slow.

Made with p5.js.
